settings.docs:
The Base URL and Basic Authentication are setup to use environment variables.

The Base URL has a default **Global** environment variable that you can edit under the Environment tab

[![GlobalEnvSnippet](GlobalEnvSnip.png)](https://github.com/jreyno77/cqf-measures/tree/master/thunder-tests/img/GlobalEnvSnip.png)

Basic Auth is setup using the **Local** environment.  In order to setup your Local Env click on the three lines under your Env tab of Thunder Client

Then choose Local Environment to enable it:

[![EnvTabSnippet](EnvTabSnippet.png)](https://github.com/jreyno77/cqf-measures/tree/master/thunder-tests/img/EnvTabSnippet.png)

Once you have enabled your Local Env you can add your *basicUser* and *basicPass* variables and those will be used for you basic Authentication within this Collection. It should look similar to with the basicUser and basicPass being the username and password to access the server you are trying to run the test against:

[![LocalEnvSnip](LocalEnvSnip.png)](https://github.com/jreyno77/cqf-measures/tree/master/thunder-tests/img/LocalEnvSnip.png)

These are then used in the Auth tab of the Collection Settings:

[![CollectionAuthSnippet](CollectionAuthSnippet.png)](https://github.com/jreyno77/cqf-measures/tree/master/thunder-tests/img/CollectionAuthSnippet.png)



### Images are broken for now, but image links are included

### Run Tests

Select Collections. In the "..." menu to the right, select "Run All", which gives you a "Run Collection" tab. In the upper right shoiuld be a "Run" button. Select that. The test should run. Green means a passing test, Red means a failing one.
Select the "Export" button and choose the format to export. We chose "Export to JSON". This file can then be imported to Microsoft Excel. Our report was that Excel file, with some editing afterwards that included highlighting and removal of some nonessential tests.

The "Docs" tab for each tests contain notes and reasons for failures.
